Background¶

This is a dataset to predict the housing price in US based on various factors such as City, House Area, No. of bedrooms and toilets, renovation status, etc.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶
Dataset Information¶

This is a dataset collected from a property agent, it contains 545 entries with 8 columns

House ID: Unique identifier for a house ranging from 0 to 544
City: Which city the house is located in
House Area: Size of the house (in square metres)
No. of Bedrooms: How many bedrooms the house has
No. of Toilets: How many toilets the house has
Stories: The number of stories in the house
Renovation Status: How well the house is renovated
Price: Price of the house (in USD)

Train-Test-Split¶

We are using train test split to split our dataset into two parts, one for training the model and one for testing the model. We will be using the 80:20 ratio

In [19]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.2, shuffle=True, random_state=42
)
X_training = X_train.copy()

City and Renovation Status are not in numerical form, so we have to change it with the help of encoding

Ordinal Encoding

  • Used for ordinal data
  • Will use on Renovation Status

One Hot Encoding

  • Used for nominal data
  • Will use on City

Here, we specify the categories for the ordinal encoding (1 --> unfurnished, 2 --> semi-furnished, 3 --> furnished), and fit the data into the encoder to change it to numerical data

We will be implementing all our preprocesses in a pipeline to prevent data leakage

In [25]:
X_train["No. of Bedrooms"] = X_train["No. of Bedrooms"].astype(str)
X_test['No. of Bedrooms'] = X_test["No. of Bedrooms"].astype(str)

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('standardize', StandardScaler(), ['House Area (sqm)']),
        ('ordinalfurnish', OrdinalEncoder(categories=[[None, 'unfurnished', 'semi-furnished', 'furnished']]), ['Renovation Status']),
        ('ordinalbedroom', OrdinalEncoder(categories=[[None, '1', '2', '3', '6', '4', '5']]), ['No. of Bedrooms']),
        ('onehot', OneHotEncoder(), ['City'])
    ],
    remainder='passthrough'  # Keep the remaining columns as they are
)

steps = [
    ("preprocessing", preprocessor),
    ("reg"),
]
step_num = len(steps) - 1

Scoring Metrics¶

I decided to evaluate my models on the r2 and rmse (root mean square error) metric.

  • r2 represents the value of how much the independent variables are able to describe the value for the target variable.
  • measures the error of the model in predicting the house price
In [26]:
scoring_methods = [
    "r2",
    "neg_mean_squared_error", 
    "neg_root_mean_squared_error", 
    "neg_mean_absolute_error", 
    "neg_mean_absolute_percentage_error"
]

I will use DummyRegressor as a baseline for our models

Note: We will be using 5 fold cross validation as the X_train only has 436 rows

def select_model(X_train, y_train, regs, scoring):
    # placeholder
    output = []
    # iterate through models
    for name, reg in regs:
        # creating temporary pipeline
        steps[step_num] = (name, reg)
        temp_pipeline = Pipeline(steps=steps)
        # cross validate
        score = cross_validate(
            temp_pipeline,
            X_train,
            y_train,
            scoring=scoring,
            n_jobs=3,
            verbose=1,
            cv=5,
            return_train_score=True,
        )
        # get the average score and then store in a Series
        output.append(pd.Series(score, name=name).apply(np.mean))
    return pd.DataFrame(output).sort_values(
        by=[
            "test_r2",
            "test_neg_root_mean_squared_error"
        ],
        ascending=False,
    )

model_scores = select_model(X_train, y_train, regs, scoring_methods)

test_scores_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Model', 'MSE', 'RMSE', 'MAE', 'MAPE', 'R2'])

def reg_report(model, y_test, y_pred):
    
    global test_scores_df

    new_row = {'Model': model,
               'MSE': metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred),
               'RMSE': metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred, squared = False),
               'MAE': metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred),
               'MAPE': metrics.mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_test, y_pred),
               'R2': metrics.r2_score(y_test, y_pred)}
    test_scores_df = pd.concat([test_scores_df, pd.DataFrame([new_row])], ignore_index=True)
    return test_scores_df

reg_report('BayesianRidge', y_test, br_y_pred)
reg_report('Ridge', y_test, ridge_y_pred)
reg_report('SGDRegressor', y_test, sgd_y_pred )
test_scores_df

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

We will be using coarse to fine tuning for hyperparameter tuning

The steps are

  1. Run RandomizedSearchCV on a range of parameters
  2. Get optimal parameters
  3. Run exhaustive search using GridSearchCV around the optimal parameters
  4. Get optimal parameters

Conclusion¶

We managed to make a machine learning model that can predict house prices in USD. We have evaluated many different models on the chosen metrics, chosen 3 models for further tuning to try to improve its performance.

However, there are still some limitations. One big limitation is the size of the data. The dataset is very small, which makes it hard for the model to try to learn and understand the data to perform better against the test data

  • I learnt that the data is really important in terms of machine learning
  • One thing I found was challenging for me was the hyperparameter tuning, which led me to research about the models that I was using and find out the parameters to be able to construct a parameter grid suitable for the tuning
